<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/2e05deae20790efe801a09e280f4911b> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Raven rattle; Tlingit; 1850-1900\r\nWood (maple), pigments and paint, thread; l. 41,7 cm. (w. handle), h. 14 cm., w. 13 cm.\r\nRMV 3134-1; purchased from art dealer Leendert Van Lier, Amsterdam 1954\r\n\r\nCalled sheishoox by the Tlingit, this type of rattle is known to outsiders under the name of “raven rattle” because it is carved in the form of a raven. This type of rattle is a unique object reaching the highest refinement of Northwest Coast art; it combines sculpture, low-relief carving and painting. Usually the raven has partly spread wings and a small red piece of wood in its beak which most likely represents the daylight, according to Tlingit mythology.\r\n\r\nSome scholars hold that the raven rattle was originally a shaman’s musical instrument, while others maintain that it was first created by the Nisga’a of the Nass River and then traded to the neighbouring tribes. However, for probably almost two centuries, the form has been reproduced and adapted by carvers of the northern and central areas of the Northwest Coast. The raven rattle has since then been used by chiefs of the various nations in a performance called the chiefs’ dance or peace dance, which dramatizes the supernatural origin of social rank. The raven rattle is part of chiefs’ regalia, which includes a headdress with a carved frontlet, a crown of sea lion whiskers and a train of ermine skins, as well as a Chilkat blanket (or a button blanket), and decorated leggings. The raven rattle is held belly up in the dancer’s hand. It is said that shaking the rattle upright may cause the raven to fly away.\r\n\r\nThis rattle conforms to the arrangement of numerous raven rattles found in museum collections. It is made of two hollowed pieces joined together by thread, forming respectively the upper part and the belly of the raven. But three outstanding features characterize this piece. The reclining  man,  whose head is resting on the raven’s ears, has the face or the mask of a bear; his back is arched on his flexed elbows and firmly planted feet on each side of the rather thick neck of the tail-bird. Both these features are not very widespread on other rattles. This part of the sculpture is deeply and cleanly carved; surely thanks to the precision of the metal tools introduced during contact. The man’s fingers and toes are realistically rendered; and its extended tongue is held in the tail’s bird bill. As usual, the breast of the raven is decorated with a stylized face with a hooked nose, said to represent a hawk. However, a third rare and specific trait of this rattle is the humanoid bird coming out of the hawk’s mouth and pinched under its nose, which adds uniqueness and singularity making this rattle very special.\r\n\r\nThe overall shape of the rattle is rather elegant because of the delicate silhouette of the reclining figure which testifies of the artistic skill of the carver. The man’s body is, as usual, red; and colour follows the standard formline use, with black primary, red as secondary, and blue as tertiary formlines. Fine adzing on the tail-bird neck and on the sides of the belly adds a particular texture to the surface of the work.\r\n\r\nMarie Mauzé\r\nLaboratoire d'Anthropologie Sociale, Paris, France; 2015\r\n\r\nSteven C. Brown, Native visions: Evolution in Northwest Coast Art from the Eighteenth through the Twentieth Century; Seattle Art Museum and University of Washington Press; Seattle, 1998. Bill Holm, The Box of Daylight: Northwest Coast Indian Art; University of Washington Press; Seattle, 1983. M-F. Guedon, Problèmes de définition du chamanisme chez les Indiens de la côte nord-ouest: l’exemple des Tsimshian; in: Culture 2/3:129-143; 1982.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nVan de Indianenstammen van de Noordwestkust van Amerika zijn talloze dansrammelaars bekend. Hieronder nemen de zogenoemde ravenrammelaars een bijzondere plaats in. Deze waren vaak zeer uitvoerig bewerkt en kwamen, afhankelijk van voorstelling en afwerking, bij uitstek in aanmerking voor gebruik door de hoofden. De rammelaar bestaat uit twee afzonderlijke delen die doorgaans met een dun stukje pees aan elkaar waren bevestigd. De voorstelling van een raaf bepaalt de vorm van het gehele voorwerp. Op zijn rug draagt hij een antropomorf figuur met een dierekop, die sterk doet denken aan een wolf. Via een lange uitstekende tong is deze verbonden met een ander dierlijk wezen, waarvan alleen de kop is weergegeven. Een verklaring van de lange tong, die bij veel rammelaars voorkomt, is niet te geven. Mogelijk wordt hiermee een overdracht van macht van het ene wezen op het andere gesymboliseerd. Wellicht zou een nadere identificatie van de uitgebeelde figuren hier enige aanwijzingen kunnen verschaffen. Ook voor de huidige stamleden is het echter vaak onmogelijk geworden tot een zekere identificatie te komen. Dit geldt ook voor de afbeeldingen aan de buikzijde van de raaf, waar een vogelachtige wezen is uitgesneden die met de snavel een ander wezen vastheeft. Gezien de grote overeenkomsten in stijl tussen de verschillende stammen - waartussen ook nauwe economische en culturele contacten bestonden - is vaak moeilijk te zeggen wat de precieze herkomst van een ratel is. De meeste werden door de Tlingit, Tsimshian en Haida gemaakt. In ieder geval lijkt Kwakiutl hier uitgesloten.\r\n\r\nEngelse tekst:\r\nNumerous dance rattles are known for the Indian tribes of the northwest coast of North America, but a special place is taken among them by what are called raven rattles. These rattles were often decorated rather elaborately, and depending on the motifs and the quality of the workmanship, were likely to be used especially by chiefs. This type of rattle was composed of two parts usually joined by a thin piece of tendon. The over-all shape was determined by the shape of the bird. On its back the raven carries an anthropomorphic figure with an animal head strongly resembling that of a wolf. This figure has a long tongue connecting it to another animal of which only the head is shown. No explanation can be offered for the long tongue seen on many rattles, but it seems possible that it symbolizes a transfer of power from one being to another. Further identification of the figures might provide some indications, but even contemporary members of the tribe often find it impossible to reach certainty about such identifications. This also holds for the figures on the abdominal part of the raven, i.e., a bird-like being holding another being in its beak. Because of the many points of agreement in style between the rattles of the various tribes - who also had strong economic and cultural contacts - it is often difficult to determine the exact provenance of a rattle. Most of them were made by Tlingit, Tsimshian, and Haida Indians. In this case, a Kwakiutl origin seems to be excluded." .
